{"_id": "21804148|None", "id": "21804148", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Br J Psychiatry; 2011 Aug; 199(2) 126-31. doi:10.1192/bjp.bp.111.091751", "year": "2011", "article-id_pmc": "PMC3623726", "type": "title", "authors": "Ryan J, Scali J, Carri\u00e8re I, Peres K, Rouaud O, Scarabin PY, Ritchie K, Ancelin ML", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Oestrogen receptor polymorphisms and late-life depression.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "1", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D000275", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "late-life depression", "locations": [{"offset": 37, "length": 20}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 59, "text": "BACKGROUND: Evidence suggests a role for oestrogen in depression but the involvement of oestrogen receptor polymorphisms remains unknown. AIMS: To determine the association between oestrogen receptor polymorphisms and late-life depression and the modifying effect of hormone treatment. METHOD: Depression was assessed using the Mini-International Neuropsychiatric Interview, according to DSM-IV criteria and the Centre for Epidemiologic Studies - Depression Scale. The association between oestrogen receptor alpha and beta (ER-alpha and ER-beta) polymorphisms with severe depression was examined in 6017 community-dwelling elderly people using multivariate logistic regression. RESULTS: In women, the ER-alpha rs2234693 and rs9340799 polymorphisms were significantly associated with the risk of late-life depression. The A allele of ER-beta rs1256049 increased the risk of depression, but only for non-current users of hormone treatment. In men, only the ER-beta rs4986938 polymorphism showed a weak association with depression risk. CONCLUSIONS: Oestrogen receptor polymorphisms are associated with severe late-life depression risk in women only.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "24", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D000275", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "depression", 